04694nam a22006975i 9780292739628DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011051988  a97802927396287 a10.7560/7396112doi  a(DE-B1597)586931  a(OCoLC)1286808037  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHE6185.U7bT493 2012 7aANT0000002bisacsh04a769.5697641 aDeaton, Charles W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great Texas Stamp Collection :bHow Some Stubborn Texas Confederate Postmasters, a Handful of Determined Texas Stamp Collectors, and a Few of the World's Greatest Philatelists Created, Discovered, and Preserved Some of the World's Most Valuable Postage Stamps /cCharles W. Deaton. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCharles N. Prothro Texana Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGlossary of Philatelic Terms -- tTime Line of Important Dates -- tCHAPTER ONE Difficult Times for Southern Postmasters and Their Customers -- tCHAPTER THREE The World’s Greatest Philatelists Acquire Their Own Texas Collections -- tCHAPTER FOUR The Printed Texas Stamps -- tCHAPTER FOUR The Printed Texas Stamps -- tCHAPTER FIVE The “Cut and Paste” Texas Stamps -- tCHAPTER SIX The “Book and Pill Label” Stamps of Gonzales -- tCHAPTER SEVEN The Curious Case of Wharton, Waxahachie, and Other “Wannabe” Texas Postmasters’ Stamps -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix. A Census of the Known Texas Confederate Postmasters’ Provisional Stamps -- tNotes on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the many difficulties the newly formed Confederate States of America endured in the summer of 1861 was the failure of its post office department to provide sufficient numbers of that item most crucial to its service: the postage stamp. Faced with the resulting din of customer complaints, a handful of industrious Texas postmasters solved the problem by simply making their own homemade stamps. In this thoroughly researched history of these rare and highly coveted stamps, The Great Texas Stamp Collection traces their journey from creation through their rediscovery years later by local, and then international, stamp collectors—a journey that culminated in the sale of a few pieces at a recent auction in New York that fetched more than $250,000. Weaving the larger contexts of Texas and U.S. postal history together with individual tales of greed, intrigue, forgery, and discovery, Deaton’s book is rich with characters from European royalty to early stamp dealers to common criminals, while also providing detailed examinations of the stamps themselves, including a complete census of the stamps now known as the Texas Confederate Postmasters’ Provisionals. Appealing at once to devoted philatelists, Texas and U.S. history buffs, and amateur collectors of all kinds, The Great Texas Stamp Collection offers a unique vantage point from which to view our history as well as the very nature of collecting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPostage stampszTexasxHistory. 0aStamp collectingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aStamp collectionszTexasxHistory. 7aANTIQUES & COLLECTIBLES / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73961140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292739628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292739628/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK